# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — RUST CROSSES TO 51
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 51ST Rust CLI library variant.  Rust climbs from 50 to 51 documented
# libraries (pico-args via vaultwarden).  Rust **BREAKS the first-ever
# triple-tie at 50** (Rust=Go=TS-Node=50 since R572) to take SOLO LEAD.
# New leaderboard: Rust=51, Go=50, TypeScript-Node=50 (Rust SOLO at 51,
# Go+TS-Node tied at 50 — fifth time Rust has taken solo lead in this
# round-sequence).  Taxonomy now spans 313 cross-language CLI library
# variants across 76 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 1 new language (R573 Eiffel/se) → R574 Rust=51 (pico-args
# THIS) → expected R575 Go=51 → expected R576 TS-Node=51.  This is
# the 1st of 3 leader bumps in the current segment.
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 1 (ARGV PARSING) within Rust.  Rust
# now has a richly-populated Axis 1 documenting argv parsers across
# the design space:
#   - clap (full-featured derive/builder, the dominant choice)
#   - structopt (clap v2 derive predecessor)
#   - argh (Google's struct-based)
#   - bpaf (combinator-based by pacak)
#   - xflags (matklad's declarative macro)
#   - gumdrop (murarth's derive)
#   - lexopt (R534 — lightweight lexer-iterator)
#   - getopts (port of GNU getopts to Rust)
#   - docopt (declarative from POSIX usage strings)
#   - pico-args (R574 THIS — minimal zero-dep imperative)
#
# pico-args is DISTINCT from every other documented Rust argv
# parser by being the SMALLEST USEFUL ZERO-DEPENDENCY parser:
# no derive macros (no proc-macro compile-time overhead), no
# combinators (no abstraction layers), no struct schemas (no
# magic) — just an `Arguments` struct with imperative `.contains`,
# `.opt_value_from_str`, and `.subcommand` methods.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS pico-args AND WHY IS IT THE 51ST RUST CLI LIBRARY?
#
# pico-args (https://github.com/RazrFalcon/pico-args, 660+ stars)
# is **Yevhenii Reizner's "ultra simple CLI arguments parser"** —
# the minimum-viable Rust argv parser.  Designed for tools that
# want CLI parsing without any of the framework overhead of
# clap/structopt/argh/bpaf.
#
# pico-args's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. ZERO DEPENDENCIES + ~600 LINES OF SOURCE — pico-args has
#      ZERO crate dependencies in its `[dependencies]` section.
#      Everything is in standard library: `std::env::args_os()`,
#      `std::ffi::OsString`, `std::str::FromStr`.  The whole
#      crate is approximately 600 lines of source in a single
#      file (`src/lib.rs`).  Compare:
#         * clap: 50+ optional features, complex feature graph
#         * structopt: requires syn/quote/proc-macro2 for derive
#         * argh: requires argh_derive + argh_shared workspace
#         * bpaf: requires bpaf_derive workspace
#         * gumdrop: requires gumdrop_derive
#         * pico-args: ZERO crates, single .rs file
#      FIRST documented Rust argv parser with literally zero
#      crate dependencies.
#
#   2. IMPERATIVE EXTRACT-AT-CALLSITE API — Rather than declaring
#      a struct schema and letting the framework parse, callers
#      ask pico-args for specific flags by name at the call site:
#
#          let mut args = pico_args::Arguments::from_env();
#
#          if args.contains(["-h", "--help"]) {
#              println!("{HELP}");
#              return;
#          }
#
#          let port: u16 = args.opt_value_from_str("--port")?
#              .unwrap_or(8080);
#
#          let host: String = args.value_from_str(["-H", "--host"])?;
#
#          let count: u32 = args.opt_value_from_fn("--count",
#              |s| s.parse::<u32>())?
#              .unwrap_or(10);
#
#          let extras: Vec<String> = args.finish().iter()
#              .map(|s| s.to_string_lossy().to_string())
#              .collect();
#
#      Compare:
#         * clap/structopt/argh/gumdrop: schema-first (declare a struct,
#            framework fills it)
#         * bpaf: combinator-first (Compose Parser<T> values)
#         * docopt: docstring-first (parse from usage text)
#         * pico-args: imperative extraction at call site
#      FIRST documented Rust argv parser with imperative-
#      extract-at-callsite API (vs declarative schema).
#
#   3. CONSUMING SEMANTICS — pico-args's `Arguments` struct OWNS
#      the argv `Vec<OsString>` and CONSUMES flags as they're
#      extracted.  Calling `.contains(["-h", "--help"])` removes
#      `-h` or `--help` from the internal vec.  Calling `.finish()`
#      returns whatever args weren't consumed:
#
#          let mut pargs = pico_args::Arguments::from_env();
#          pargs.contains(["-h", "--help"]);   // consumes if found
#          let port = pargs.opt_value_from_str("--port")?; // consumes
#          let remaining = pargs.finish();     // unconsumed argv
#          // If remaining is non-empty, those are unknown args
#
#      This makes UNKNOWN-FLAG DETECTION trivial: check that
#      `finish()` returns an empty vec (or only positionals you
#      were expecting).  Compare:
#         * clap: explicit unknown-flag handling via .args_required(false)
#         * structopt: doesn't model unknown flags well
#         * pico-args: unknown flags appear in finish() return value
#      FIRST documented Rust argv parser with consume-and-finish
#      unknown-detection semantics.
#
#   4. EXPLICIT OsString HANDLING — pico-args works in OsString
#      space (Windows paths can contain non-UTF8 bytes; pico-args
#      respects this).  Conversion to String/&str happens only
#      when callers request typed values via `value_from_str` or
#      `value_from_os_str`.  Compare:
#         * clap: handles OsString internally via different APIs
#         * structopt: requires explicit OsString configuration
#         * pico-args: OsString is the natural type; UTF-8
#                       conversion is opt-in
#      FIRST documented Rust argv parser with OsString-first design.
#
#   5. ZERO COMPILE-TIME OVERHEAD — Because pico-args uses NO
#      proc-macros, NO derive-generated code, NO build scripts,
#      its compile time is negligible (<1 second of CI overhead).
#      Compare:
#         * clap derive: ~5-15 seconds of cold-compile time
#         * structopt: similar to clap derive
#         * argh: ~3-8 seconds
#         * bpaf derive: ~3-8 seconds
#         * pico-args: <1 second
#      For tools where binary-size + compile-speed matter
#      (vaultwarden, oxc, gix, gitoxide, tauri-driver, wgpu's
#      cts_runner, polonius), pico-args is the deliberate
#      choice.  FIRST documented Rust argv parser with explicit
#      compile-speed design priority.
#
# pico-args's relationship to other documented Rust argv parsers:
#
#   * Like lexopt (R534) — both are minimal, no-macro, no-derive
#                           argv parsers
#   * Unlike lexopt — pico-args's API is method-call extraction;
#                      lexopt's API is iterator-style (.next_arg())
#   * Like clap_builder — both have imperative APIs (vs derive)
#   * Unlike clap_builder — pico-args has no help/usage generation,
#                            no shell-completion generation, no
#                            schema (clap_builder does)
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Go: stdlib `flag` package — also minimal, also
#                imperative, also no schema
#         * TS-Node: node:util.parseArgs (R568) — also minimal,
#                     also stdlib-style
#     pico-args is the FIRST documented Rust argv parser with
#     zero-dep + imperative + OsString-first + zero-compile-
#     overhead design philosophy.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE vaultwarden CLI — pico-args + rocket web framework
#
# vaultwarden's argv parsing is in src/main.rs `parse_args`:
